[normal]3.10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Figure 21 focuses on the Haltemprice area which is identified as one of the top 3 key areas where a bus network would provide access 
[normal]for residents to key services. 
[normal]There is a strong need for multi-service routes running through Cottingham, Kirkella and Anl
[normal]aby and into Willerby, as well as a lower level of support in Hessle.  The two blue road sections present on the map, particularly the road in 
[normal]Cottingham, demonstrate where a bus service would be used by residents accessing all 6 different key services and
[normal] would therefore be highly recommended as a potential public transport route. The South Holderness has already been identified as an area of high rurality and deprivation on a number of different levels from income to car ownership and this is mirrored in 
[normal]the routes that Scenario 1 has identified. The routes from Keyingham to Withernsea along the A1033, and towards Easington on the B1433 are heavily populated with routes of more than 3 different services. There is also a strong case for providing public tra
[normal]nsport to the West of Keyingham towards Thorngumbald and Hedon, especially given the sparse nature of the region. Figure 22 clearly identifies issues that residents living in Roos, Burton Pidsea, Burstwick, Sproatley, Bilton and Preston will have accessing
[normal] key services.
